      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "```python\ndef solve_weighted_intervals(intervals):\n    \"\"\"\n    This function solves the weighted interval scheduling problem.\n    It takes a list of intervals (start, end, weight) as input and returns the maximum weight possible without overlapping.\n\n    :param intervals: A list of tuples (start, end, weight)\n    :return: The maximum weight possible without overlapping\n    \"\"\"\n    intervals.sort(key=lambda x: x[1])  # sort intervals by end time\n    weight = 0  # initialize weight\n    prev_end = -1  # initialize previous end time\n\n    for start, end, w in intervals:\n        if start >= prev_end:  # if current interval doesn't overlap with previous one\n            weight += w  # add current weight to total weight\n            prev_end = end  # update previous end time\n\n    return weight\n```\nThis function sorts the intervals by their end times, then iterates over them, adding the weight of each non-overlapping interval to the total weight. The `prev_end` variable keeps track of the end time of the previous non-overlapping interval. If the current interval doesn't overlap with the previous one, its weight is added to the total weight.",
